============================================================
HANDLING CONFLICTING EVIDENCE
============================================================
What happens when observations conflict with current beliefs?
Strong beliefs resist change, weak beliefs change more easily.

Scenario: Strong evidence for State B arrives
Likelihood (obs=1): [0.05 0.9  0.05]

Strong prior belief:
  Prior:     [0.9  0.05 0.05]
  Posterior: [0.48648649 0.48648649 0.02702703]
  Change:    [-0.41351351  0.43648649 -0.02297297]

Weak prior belief:
  Prior:     [0.5 0.3 0.2]
  Posterior: [0.08196721 0.8852459  0.03278689]
  Change:    [-0.41803279  0.5852459  -0.16721311]

Key insights:
- Strong beliefs resist conflicting evidence
- Weak beliefs are more easily updated
- This creates 'belief inertia' in inference

Overcoming strong beliefs with repeated evidence:
Step 1: [0.48648649 0.48648649 0.02702703]
Step 2: [0.05247813 0.94460641 0.00291545]
Belief flipped to State B after 2 steps!

